@node fleecy "FLEECY DISCLOSE SOME INTERESTING NEWS"
                     FLEECY DISCLOSE SOME INTERESTING NEWS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Every last Wednesday Fleecy Moss, Vice President of Product Development for the
new Amiga Inc., attend to a live conference in the only-for-members AmigaZone's
chat area.

The last conference, held on the evening of February 23, 2000, was a little bit
boring because there was not a lot of people asking questions to Fleecy. Anyway,
he disclosed some interesting things about the future.

First, Fleecy said that Amiga Inc. have a new office, a new VP of operations
whose name is Vince Pfeiffer, and they just did their latest round of training
in the Tao system which took place in Seattle.

Amiga have a development team (a dozen or so), a developer support manager and
team (14), the AAC has been restarted, they are trying to get the ADN (= Amiga
Dealer Network) moving again, they have a VP of operations whose name is Vince
Pfeiffer, the new website is close to being ready, and they are working on
something nice for the community.

Quite a few of the people they are hiring will be very familiar to the community
but apart from Dean K. Brown, no one from the old days. When the new website
comes up we will know more names. Fleecy had hoped the new Director of Developer
support would be up by now but it seems Bill was busy moving. By the way, the
director of developer support is someone you all know and love, but we are not
going to know his name until the press release.

There are no real news about the liquidation of the remaining A1200s. Petro is
slowly selling them into India, where there is a big demand for them. Bill is
getting a pallet NTSC'd to bring over. They are looking at another possibility
which could return some real rewards for everyone.

Bill is very concerned about the dealers. People have stopped buying as they
wait and Amiga want them to understand that they should buy the SW because they
are working with H&P to ensure it works on the new Amiga. It isn't wasted.

Fleecy, Bill and the director of developer support are trying to sort out
something for the developers - they have some legal stuff to take care of soon.
All the announcements they had thought would be nicely spread out will probably
all arrive at the same time.

If people is worried about the performance of the Tao's Virtual Processor, They
should know that Tao gives transparent multi-processor parallelism. Amiga are
also looking at some technology that could turn the internet from treacle to
better than TV whilst being fully interactive.

With respect the software, the problem with that is Amiga could end up doing a
Be and spend more time writing drivers than developing their core product. What
Amiga need is a unified driver model - HAVi will hopefully allow them to get
there.

Amiga will start at one developer conference a year, a full serious and
commercial developer thing with most of the developer leads there, for some
serious work and play. As they expand, so they will.

The Amiga Advisory Council will be developed to its full potential. It was
Bill's idea after all. Collas just got the credit for it. They are also doing
something on the new site that will try to be a focus for the community, give
them an opportunity to participate, belong etc.

H&P are going to create product for the new Amiga, work with Amiga on creating a
classic emulator, and perhaps, if they can swing it, do a set of transitional
releases that help move developer and user from the old to the new.

The eagerly awaited developer box will come out in the next few months, probably
in April. With it Amiga are taking a risk because there won't be much Amie in
it, since they are still developing it, but they can get their hands on
something.
